  "findings": [
    "1. Conservative AADWD \u2248 Fixed WD: acc diff=0.17%, WN diff=0.11. Because (1-\u03b4) \u2248 1.0 when \u03b4 is O(10\u207b\u00b3), conservative barely adapts. This validates that the alignment signal is small but detectable.",
    "2. Square variant WN=38.75 (highest among WD methods). \u03bb = c\u00b7lr\u00b2\u00b7(1-\u03b4): after lr drops 0.1\u21920.01\u21920.001, \u03bb drops by 100\u00d7/10000\u00d7. Effective WD vanishes in late training. Not recommended without LR-decoupling.",
    "3. Aggressive variant is the only true dynamic method (\u03bb \u221d \u03b4). Best=92.05%, WN=21.47. \u03bb adapts to alignment state, providing stronger regularization when gradients are more aligned with parameters.",
    "4. CWD instability: best=91.79% \u2192 final=86.95% (\u0394=4.84%). Final WN=9.28 (lowest). Over-aggressive coordinate-wise decay leads to catastrophic weight shrinkage in late training.",
    "5. Best AADWD variant: aadwd_conservative (92.37%). For cross-arch validation, use both conservative (best acc but \u2248fixed WD) and aggressive (true dynamics) to distinguish structural vs accidental gains."
  ],
